1. φ : mapping from states to a vector representation used to approximate the value, 2. ω : value function approximation parameters, 3. ζ : mapping from states to a vector representation used to approximate the policy, 4. θ : policy parameters, 5. α : the value learning rate (fast learning rate), 6. β : the policy learning rate (slow learning rate, i.e., β < α), and 7. (s, a, s′, r) : a state-action-next-state-reward tuple.
1: V̂NEW ← ( r + γ ∑ a′∈A πθ(a ′|s′)ωTφ(s, a′) ) {Estimate V πθ given the new sample.} 2: V̂OLD ← ωTφ(s, a) {Use the current value function approximation to estimate the value.} 3: δ ← ( V̂NEW − V̂OLD ) {Compute the temporal difference error.} 4: ω′ ← ω + αδ { Update the value function weights using the fast learning rate α. } 5: ψs,a ← ζ(s, a)−
∑ a′∈A πθ(a ′, s)ζ(s, a′) {Compute the “compatible features” Bhatnagar et al. [2009]. }
6: θ′ ← θ + βδψs,a { Update the policy parameters using the slow learning rate β. } 7: Return 〈ω′, θ′〉 { Updated value function and policy parameters. }
Although using different representations for approximating the value function and the policy strictly violates the policy gradient theorem Sutton et al. [2000], it still tends to work well in practice.
In our experiments, we used a fast learning rate of α = 0.1 and a slow learning rate of β = 0.2α. Value function and policy parameters were initialized to zero vectors.
